<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a DRIP (dividend reinvestment plan)?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A DRIP automatically uses each dividend payment to buy more shares (including fractional shares) of the same investment instead of depositing cash. Every reinvested dividend increases your share count, and every new share generates its own dividends — a compounding loop where your income buys the assets that raise your income. Most brokers offer free automatic reinvestment on stocks, ETFs, and funds."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does dividend reinvestment compound?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "DRIP compounds your share count, not just your account value. Two engines run at once: the dividend per share grows (companies raising payouts), and your number of shares grows (reinvestment buying more). Your annual income is shares × dividend per share, so it grows at roughly the product of both rates — meaningfully faster than either alone. That's why long-horizon DRIP income charts curve upward instead of climbing in a straight line."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Are reinvested dividends taxable?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes — in a taxable account, dividends are taxed the year they're paid whether or not you take them as cash. Reinvestment doesn't defer anything: you'll owe tax on money you never saw, paid from other funds. Qualified dividends get capital-gains rates (0%, 15%, or 20%); non-qualified get ordinary rates. Each reinvestment also adds a new tax lot with its own cost basis. Inside an IRA or 401(k), none of this applies — which is why income-heavy holdings often belong in tax-advantaged accounts."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is a high dividend yield or high dividend growth better?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "It's a time-horizon trade. High yield pays more now but usually grows slowly; high growth pays little now but raises the payout fast. A 3% yield growing 6% a year overtakes a 6% yield growing 1% a year in annual income within about 15 years — and keeps pulling away. Long horizons favor growers; investors who need income today favor yield. Extremely high yields (8%+) are often a warning sign, not a gift."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a dividend yield trap?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A yield that looks generous because the share price has collapsed in anticipation of a dividend cut. Yield = dividend ÷ price, so a falling price inflates the yield right up until the payout is slashed. Signs: payout ratio near or above 100% of earnings, declining revenue, and a yield far above sector peers. When the cut comes, you lose the income and usually more price. Check payout sustainability before chasing any double-digit yield."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is yield on cost?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Your current annual dividend income divided by what you originally paid — a measure of how far the income snowball has rolled. Hold a 3%-yielding stock that grows its dividend 6% annually for 30 years with reinvestment, and your yield on cost can exceed 40%: the position pays you 40%+ of your original investment every year. It's a motivating metric, though for decisions today, current yield and expected growth matter more."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I reinvest dividends or take the cash?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Reinvest during accumulation — every dividend taken as cash is compounding you cancelled. Take the cash when you actually need the income (typically retirement) or when you want to redirect it: rebalancing into other assets, funding an underweight position, or covering the taxes the dividends themselves generate in a taxable account. The switch from reinvesting to collecting is one of the cleanest retirement transitions there is."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do DRIPs buy fractional shares?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes — that's one of their quiet advantages. A $47 dividend buys exactly $47 of stock even if a share costs $500, so every dollar goes to work immediately with no cash drag. Broker DRIPs do this automatically and commission-free at virtually all major brokerages, and some legacy company-sponsored plans even reinvest at a small discount to market price."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can dividends be cut?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Absolutely — dividends are a board decision, not a contract. Recessions produce waves of cuts (2008-09 and 2020 both did), and individual companies cut when earnings can't cover the payout. This calculator assumes smooth, uninterrupted growth, which is optimistic for any single stock. Diversified dividend ETFs make the smooth-growth assumption far more defensible than concentrated positions do."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does dividend investing beat growth investing?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Neither reliably beats the other — total return (price growth plus dividends) is what compounds, and the market doesn't pay a premium just for the money arriving as a check. Dividends aren't free money: the share price drops by roughly the dividend on the ex-date. The real cases for dividend strategies are behavioral (visible, rising income is easy to hold through crashes) and structural (income without selling shares). Just don't sacrifice diversification for yield."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How accurate is a dividend reinvestment calculator?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "It's a projection, not a promise. This one assumes steady dividend growth, steady price growth, and annual reinvestment — real dividends arrive quarterly, prices swing daily, and growth rates wander. Treat the output as the shape of the compounding, not a forecast of the destination. The direction of the conclusion — reinvesting beats collecting cash over long horizons — is robust; the exact dollar figures are not."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do reinvested dividends complicate my taxes?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Somewhat, in taxable accounts. Every reinvestment creates a new tax lot, so after a decade of quarterly DRIPs you may have 40+ lots with different cost bases. Modern brokers track this automatically and report it on your 1099-B when you sell, so the burden is mostly historical — but keep your records if you transfer brokers, and remember every reinvested dollar raises your total cost basis, reducing your eventual capital gain."
      }
    }
  ]
}
